{
  "id": "019d286a-f2d8-78b2-92cd-6ae9c98189a3",
  "content": "# M3.3: Embedding & Chunking Strategy Design\n\n## Summary\n\nAdd a trait-based chunking framework to `corvia-kernel` that standardizes how all content is split, merged, and prepared for embedding. A `ChunkingStrategy` trait lets adapters provide domain-specific chunking logic (AST for code, heading-based for markdown) while the kernel's `ChunkingPipeline` enforces universal quality concerns: token budget limits, oversized chunk splitting, small chunk merging, and overlap context. A `FormatRegistry` routes file formats to strategies with hybrid auto-detect + adapter overrides.\n\n\n## Motivation\n\n1. **Silent truncation.** Embedding engines hard-cap at 4000 chars (`MAX_EMBED_CHARS`). Large functions or long documents get silently truncated — lost information with no feedback.\n\n2. **Prose is chunked as whole-files.** Markdown, TOML, YAML, JSON, and PDF files go through as single chunks. A 50-page README or a long `Cargo.toml` becomes one embedding, destroying retrieval granularity.\n\n3. **No universal enforcement.** Token limits, overlap, and merging are universal concerns but currently don't exist anywhere. Each adapter would need to independently implement them — duplicated, unenforced, error-prone.\n\n4. **Multi-format repos are the norm.** A single Git repo contains code, docs, configs, and sometimes PDFs. Each format needs different chunking semantics, but all need the same quality guarantees.\n\n5. **Benchmarking readiness.** Trait-based strategies let M6 eval swap chunking approaches and measure downstream retrieval quality without code changes.\n",
  "source_version": "docs/rfcs/2026-03-02-m3.3-embedding-chunking-design.md",
